wor=\r\nd of Adi Shankara is gospel and perfect truth, I invite them to read his co=\r\nmmentary on &quot;Ishavasyopanishad&quot; (aka &quot;Ishopanishad&quot;). One can certainly vie=\r\nw it as the great Shankara tying himself in knots! THAT upanishad really ch=\r\nallenges the simplified main message Shankara chose to drive home in THAT i=\r\nncarnation!\n=A0\nContrast it with how Sri Aurobindo does justice to that key=\r\n Upanishad!\n=A0\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n--------\nAstrology & Spirituality R=\r\nesources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org \n--------\n=A0=A0\n\n=A0\n\nOn Thu, Oct=\r\n 11, 2012 at 5:26 PM, rajarshi nandy wrote:\n=A0\nDear Utpal, \n=A0\n&lt;&lt; \nIt may=\r\n require a LOT to reject philosophy of giant such as adi Shankara and yet s=\r\nome one may not be able to reject afterall. &gt;&gt; \n\nPhilosophy is pure rationa=\r\nl thought. Spirituality on the other hand is experiential. One can sit in a=\r\nn armchair and contemplate on philosophy, but the same is not possible in c=\r\nase of spirituality. These two are different. Philosophy gives a logical fr=\r\namework of understanding something. There could be philosophy of science, a=\r\n philosophy of ethics, a philosophy of spirituality, a philosophy of episte=\r\nmology (the investigations into the process of acquiring knowledge) etc. \n\n=\r\nThat Sri Adi Shankara was a fantastic spiritual giant, I have no doubt (whi=\r\nch I have already stated in my previous email. Vibhuti of God). I am also s=\r\nure that the very presence of such a man of such spiritual stature would ha=\r\nve naturally drawn masses towards him.=A0 It happens with all great persona=\r\nlities. They have a magnetism which extends=A0 way beyond after their death=\r\n. \n\nHowever, to understand, appreciate, criticize, debate, analyses, compar=\r\natively-evaluate any philosophy of any individual is not that difficult and=\r\n is a valid rational process. \n\nWhile future is always uncertain, but chanc=\r\nes look remote for me that I would find Mayavada more attractive. It was Sr=\r\ni Adi Shankara&#39;s Mayavada - as is understood and propagated by his follower=\r\ns - which I had studied when I was first trying to get a grasp of Hindu phi=\r\nlosophy. It a nice, compact and easily understandable philosophy. Possibly =\r\none the chief reasons why most=A0 intellectuals like his Adwaitha apart fro=\r\nm being attracted by his personality. It is easier to debate from Sri Shank=\r\nara&#39;s stand-point. At that time I liked it. Later as I got acquainted mysel=\r\nf with more varieties of Hindu philosophy, I found others more comprehensiv=\r\ne and covering more essential points and using a very, if I may use this ph=\r\nrase, a bottom-up=A0 approach to understanding reality, while Sri Shankara&#39;=\r\ns philosophy is a very top-down approach, with a greater thrust on the top =\r\nand an indeterminate leftover in the bottom. Shankara&#39;s Adwaitha, Ramanujac=\r\nharya&#39;s Visistha-adwaitha,\n Vallavacharya&#39;s Suddha Adwaitha - so many varie=\r\nties of philosophy. \n\nI have a personal view about judging philosophy. For =\r\neverything that one giant has said, there is always another one who has sai=\r\nd exactly the opposite. And a third and forth one who came up with a differ=\r\nent view-point, differing with all the previous ones. And each of these gia=\r\nnts have spoken with the utmost conviction of their own realizations of tru=\r\nths. So personality and stature of the philosopher should play no role in a=\r\nn objective analysis of the philosophy. Just like the personality and statu=\r\nre of a mathematician is of no use in=A0 judging the correctness of a mathe=\r\nmatical theory.=A0 Spiritually, the reality is same (and it maybe a very=A0=\r\n complex reality). But philosophically each have differences which cannot t=\r\nhe ignored. In such an intellectual climate, in my personal opinion, it is =\r\nfair enough to discard one philosophy for another, after a thorough and det=\r\nailed contemplation of the pros and cons. \n\nFrom a spiritual view-point all=\r\n this is utterly meaningless. Which ever spiritual giant one chooses to han=\r\ng on to, if sincere faith, reverence and effort is engaged, surely progress=\r\n will happen in time. But philosophy is a another matter. \n\n[To make my sta=\r\nnd clearer, let me say hypothetically that IF by some strange miracle of Go=\r\nd, Sri Adi Shankara were to come and stand infornt of me, I would have no q=\r\nualms about falling at his feet and bowing down to him and asking for his b=\r\nlessings, for his spiritual stature is unquestionable. Yet I will still not=\r\n be agreeable to the philosophy he propagated during the time he lived.] \n\n=\r\n-Best=A0 Regards \n=A0Rajarshi \n\n\n\n\nawaktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabudd=\r\nhayah | \nparam bhAwamajAnanto mamAwyayamanuttamam ||[7:24] \n\n\n_____________=\r\n______________________\n\nFrom: vedic_pathak &lt;vedic_pathak@...&gt; \nTo: ve=\r\ndic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com \nSent: Thursday, 11 October 2012 10:32 PM \nSubje=\r\nct: [vedic-wisdom] Re: A thought \n\n=A0 Dear Rajarshi, \n\n&gt;&gt;&gt;Yet, I have equa=\r\nlly no qualms in rejecting his philosophy&lt;&lt;&lt; \n\nactually &quot;rejecting&quot; may not=\r\n be the right word you probably mistakenly used. It could be that it does n=\r\not attract you that much incomparision to the other one and/or as in case o=\r\nf Aurobindo&#39;s philosophy which did not make sense earlier and which now mak=\r\nes a lot of sense. same way, it is possible for Adi Shankara&#39;s adwait. \n\nIt=\r\n may require a LOT to reject philosophy of giant such as adi Shankara and y=\r\net some one may not be able to reject afterall. That is MHO. \n\nBest Regards=\r\n, \n\nUtpal \n\n--- In vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com, rajarshi nandy &lt;rajarshi14=\r\n@...&gt; wrote: \n&gt; \n&gt; Dear Lakshmi Narayan ji, \n&gt; \n&gt; I am doing fine. I hope y=\r\nour health is fine too. \n&gt; \n&gt; I will answer th