r so. I could not believe \n&gt; what I was reading=\r\n. Then my respect for this yogi went down the drain.&gt;&gt; \n&gt; \n&gt; You surety is =\r\nincorrect. There were certain events which happened in the last one and hal=\r\nf years which made me sit down and rethink my own understanding of spiritua=\r\nlity. At about the same time I started worshiping a specific personality of=\r\n the Divine Mother, and the more I meditated on Her, the more would thought=\r\ns pour into my mind that my understanding of spirituality is imperfect and =\r\nhas serious flaws. I tried, using my own meditations to find out what was w=\r\nrong or rather imperfectly understood, what needed rethinking. First questi=\r\non I asked myself was, what is the aim of spirituality? My mind could grasp=\r\n some outlines of certain answers and processes and truths. But it was stil=\r\nl not exceptionally clear. \n&gt; \n&gt; I had first read Sri Aurobindo when I was =\r\nin college. I could not go beyond the first two pages. They were bouncers g=\r\noing one mile over my head. Three years ago someone gave me a book of Sri A=\r\nurobindo. I could understand say 10 percent, and rest I rejected, partly du=\r\ne to ignorance and partly due to egoistic arrogance. Never opened any of hi=\r\ns writing since then. This year, as my sadhana was going on and as I was in=\r\nstinctively trying to correct the flaws in my understanding, one day while =\r\nmeditating I had an inner thought in the form of an image, which told me th=\r\nat I should start reading Sri Aurobindo but in a very specific manner. The =\r\nimage was very clear in my inner-eye, and thoroughly pressing on my conscio=\r\nusness. I opened his book again, and read it in the prescribed manner and t=\r\nhis time it made a LOT of sense to me. What I was struggling to understand =\r\nall this year, whose outline I could grasp yet not get a proper hang of, I =\r\nwas able to=A0 understand \n&gt;=A0 from his writings with much deeper clarity.=\r