h is sufficiently captured=\r\n by Veda and Upanishad. That way, there is no need for any additional works=\r\n. Though people cannot comprehend them and need someone to comment on them,=\r\n nobody can capture the Truth more perfectly than Veda and Upanishad. So, w=\r\nhat ends up happening is that one focuses on a small part of the Truth\n cap=\r\ntured by them and explains it in the desa-kala-patra of one&#39;s times.&lt;br&gt;&nb=\r\nsp;&lt;br&gt;Shankaraka wrote commentaries on the ageless Truths of Upanishad, as=\r\n per his desa-kala-patra. Now, people can&#39;t understand even his commentary =\r\nas it was meant. So there are further commentaries on his commentaries, bas=\r\ned on OUR desa-kala-patra!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;(4) The goal of a master is often n=\r\not to write something perfect (if so, Veda and Upanishad are already there)=\r\n, but to write something more direct and useful to one&#39;s audience. Every ma=\r\nster may come with a mission and focus on that mission. Adi Shankara&#39;s prim=\r\nary mission was to stop the advance of Buddhism and show how tenets of Budd=\r\nhism are contained in Vedanta.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;(5) If one thinks (like a learn=\r\ned friend of mine does) that every word of Adi Shankara is gospel and perfe=\r\nct truth, I invite them to read his commentary on &quot;Ishavasyopanishad&quot; (aka =\r\n&quot;Ishopanishad&quot;). One can certainly view it as the great Shankara\n tying him=\r\nself in knots! THAT upanishad really challenges the simplified main message=\r\n Shankara chose to drive home in THAT incarnation!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Contrast it=\r\n with how Sri Aurobindo does justice to that key Upanishad!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Be=\r\nst regards,&lt;br&gt;Narasimha&lt;br&gt;--------&lt;br&gt;Astrology &amp; Spirituality Resour=\r\nces: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org &lt;br&gt;--------&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;spa=\r\nn&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color: rgb