ada =\r\n- as is understood and propagated by his followers - which I had studied wh=\r\nen I was first trying to get a grasp of Hindu philosophy. It a nice, compac=\r\nt and easily understandable philosophy. Possibly one the chief reasons why =\r\nmost&nbsp; intellectuals like his Adwaitha apart from being attracted by hi=\r\ns personality. It is easier to debate from Sri Shankara&#39;s stand-point. At t=\r\nhat time I liked it. Later as I got acquainted myself with more varieties o=\r\nf Hindu philosophy, I found others more comprehensive and covering more ess=\r\nential points and using a very, if I may use this phrase, a bottom-up&nbsp;=\r\n approach to understanding reality, while Sri Shankara&#39;s philosophy is a ve=\r\nry top-down approach, with a\n greater thrust on the top and an indeterminat=\r\ne leftover in the bottom. Shankara&#39;s Adwaitha, Ramanujacharya&#39;s Visistha-ad=\r\nwaitha, Vallavacharya&#39;s Suddha Adwaitha - so many varieties of philosophy. =\r\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I have a personal view about judging philosophy. For everything tha=\r\nt one giant has said, there is always another one who has said exactly the =\r\nopposite. And a third and forth one who came up with a different view-point=\r\n, differing with all the previous ones. And each of these giants have spoke=\r\nn with the utmost conviction of their own realizations of truths. So person=\r\nality and stature of the philosopher should play no role in an objective an=\r\nalysis of the philosophy. Just like the personality and stature of a mathem=\r\natician is of no use in&nbsp; judging the correctness of a mathematical the=\r\nory.&nbsp; Spiritually, the reality is same (and it maybe a very&nbsp; comp=\r\nlex reality). But philosophically each have differences which cannot the ig=\r\nnored. In such an\n intellectual climate, in my personal opinion, it is fair=\r\n enough to discard one philosophy for another, after a thorough and detaile=\r\nd contemplation of the pros and cons. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;From a spiritual view-point a=\r\nll this is utterly meaningless. Which ever spiritual giant one chooses to h=\r\nang on to, if sincere faith, reverence and effort is engaged, surely progre=\r\nss will happen in time. But philosophy is a another matter. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;[To mak=\r\ne my stand clearer, let me say hypothetically that IF by some strange mirac=\r\nle of God, Sri Adi Shankara were to come and stand infornt of me, I would h=\r\nave no qualms about falling at his feet and bowing down to him and asking f=\r\nor his blessings, for his spiritual stature is unquestionable. Yet I will s=\r\ntill not be agreeable to the philosophy he propagated during the time he li=\r\nved.] &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;-Best&nbsp; Regards &lt;br&gt;&nbsp;Rajarshi &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;aw=\r\naktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah | &lt;br&gt;param bhAwamajAnanto\n mam=\r\nAwyayamanuttamam ||[7:24] &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;___________________________________&lt;b=\r\nr&gt;&lt;br&gt;From: vedic_pathak &lt;vedic_pathak@...&gt; &lt;br&gt;To: vedic-wisdo=\r\nm@yahoogroups.com &lt;br&gt;Sent: Thursday, 11 October 2012 10:32 PM &lt;br&gt;Subject:=\r\n [vedic-wisdom] Re: A thought &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&nbsp; Dear Rajarshi, &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&gt;&gt=\r\n;&gt;Yet, I have equally no qualms in rejecting his philosophy&lt;&lt;&lt; =\r\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;actually &quot;rejecting&quot; may not be the right word you probably mistake=\r\nnly used. It could be that it does not attract you that much incomparision =\r\nto the other one and/or as in case of Aurobindo&#39;s philosophy which did not =\r\nmake sense earlier and which now makes a lot of sense. same way, it is poss=\r\nible for Adi Shankara&#39;s adwait. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;It may require a LOT to reject phil=\r\nosophy of giant such as adi Shankara and yet some one may not be able to re=\r\nject afterall. That is MHO. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Best Regards, &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Utpal &l